{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"80840b9f-f1ee-432f-8aad-acb73091dd77","content":"Here's the diagnosis and recommendations:\n\n## Root Cause\n\nThe developer report nails it: **MSBuild process startup and project re-evaluation** on every `dotnet build` invocation. Visual Studio avoids this by keeping MSBuild nodes alive in-process. The CLI, by default, does **not** reuse MSBuild nodes (`MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE=1`).\n\nThe `.csproj` itself is clean — the fix is in **how** builds are invoked.\n\n## Recommendations (ordered by impact)\n\n### 1. Use `dotnet watch build` for the inner loop\nKeeps the process alive and only rebuilds on file changes — eliminates startup cost entirely:\n```\ndotnet watch build\n```\n\n### 2. Enable the MSBuild Build Server (.NET 8+)\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\ndotnet build\n```\nThis keeps an MSBuild server process running between CLI invocations, similar to how VS works.\n\n### 3. Enable MSBuild node reuse\n```bash\nexport MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE=0\ndotnet build -nodeReuse:true\n```\nKeeps MSBuild worker nodes alive between builds instead of spawning new ones each time.\n\n### 4. Use graph-based builds\n```bash\ndotnet build -graph\n```\nStatic graph evaluation avoids redundant project re-evaluation.\n\n---\n\n**For the fastest edit-build-test cycle**, use **`dotnet watch build`** — it sidesteps the entire startup problem. For teams that prefer explicit `dotnet build` invocations, set `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` in your shell profile.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"80891f5e-84aa-4b6d-9b91-3df2e7f23bdc","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer reports that CLI builds are slow (2-4 seconds) for incremental builds even when nothing changed, while Visual Studio builds are nearly instant. The key insight from the report is:\n\n> The overhead seems to come from MSBuild process startup and re-evaluation of the project graph on every CLI invocation.\n\nThis is a well-known issue. The reason Visual Studio is fast is that it keeps an MSBuild server process running in the background, avoiding the startup cost on each build.\n\nThe solutions are:\n\n1. **Use the MSBuild Server (`-tl` / terminal logger with build server)**: Starting with .NET 8, MSBuild has a build server feature that keeps the MSBuild process alive between builds, similar to what Visual Studio does. You can enable it with:\n   - `dotnet build /p:UseSharedCompilation=true` to activate the Roslyn compiler server (usually enabled by default)\n   - `set DOTNET_CLI_DO_NOT_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=0` or `-nodeReuse:true` to ensure MSBuild node reuse is active\n\n2. **Use `dotnet watch`**: For development workflows, `dotnet watch` keeps the process running and only rebuilds when files change, eliminating the startup overhead entirely.\n\n3. **Enable the MSBuild Build Server**: In .NET 8+, you can configure `<UseSharedCompilation>true</UseSharedCompilation>` in your project to ensure the shared compilation server stays active between builds.\n\n4. **Use the `-graph` flag**: `dotnet build -graph` leverages static graph evaluation for potentially faster builds.\n\n5. **MSBuild node reuse**: The `-nodeReuse:true` flag (or `/nr:true`) keeps MSBuild worker nodes alive between builds instead of spinning them up fresh each time. This is disabled by default in `dotnet build` but enabled in Visual Studio, which is why builds feel faster there.\n\nThe most impactful change is enabling the MSBuild Build Server, particularly in .NET 8+, using the `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER` environment variable to keep the server running across builds. dotnet build spawns a fresh process each time, requiring the runtime to start up and reload everything from scratch. The real solutions are using `dotnet watch build` to skip process restarts entirely, enabling the MSBuild server in .NET 8+ with an environment variable to keep a persistent build process, disabling node reuse restrictions that the CLI enforces by default, or leveraging static graph builds for better parallelization.","outputTokens":1403,"requestId":"7404:D40E:15ECD1B:187B39B:6A051E35"},"id":"ec4971a4-148d-45a6-8ec2-2f86bc56c193","timestamp":"2026-05-14T00:58:57.868Z","parentId":"dcccd8e1-0609-4fd9-a51a-f6f7a08ff019"}
